SIMPLE: squilgee
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Squilgee
<hw>Squil"gee</hw> <pr>(skw⟦icr⟧l"j⟦esl⟧)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<def>Formerly, a small swab for drying a vessel's deck; now, a kind of
scraper having a blade or edge of rubber or of leather, -- used for
removing superfluous water or other liquids, as from a vessel's deck
after washing, from window panes, photographer's plates, etc.</def>
<altsp>[Written also <asp>squillgee</asp>, <asp>squillagee</asp>,
<asp>squeegee.</asp>]</altsp>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Squilgee</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Squilgee
<hw>Squil"gee</hw> <pr>(skw⟦icr⟧l"j⟦esl⟧)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Squilgeed</conjf>
<pr>(skw⟦icr⟧l"j⟦emac⟧d)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Squilgeeing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To swab, press, or treat with
a squilgee; <as>as, to <ex>squilgee</ex> a vessel's deck</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Squill</ent>⟦br⟧
